04462nam a22006255i 9780226547404DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265474047 a10.7208/97802265474042doi  a(DE-B1597)523235  a(OCoLC)1035556708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aJA74.5b.B458 2019 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a320.012231 ade Beistegui, Miguel, eauthor.14aThe Government of Desire :bA Genealogy of the Liberal Subject /cMiguel de Beistegui. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Why Desire? -- tPart One. Homo Oeconomicus -- tPart Two. Homo Sexualis -- tPart Three. Homo Symbolicus -- tConclusion. Desire, Again ... -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLiberalism, Miguel de Beistegui argues in The Government of Desire, is best described as a technique of government directed towards the self, with desire as its central mechanism.  Whether as economic interest, sexual drive, or the basic longing for recognition, desire is accepted as a core component of our modern self-identities, and something we ought to cultivate. But this has not been true in all times and all places. For centuries, as far back as late antiquity and early Christianity, philosophers believed that desire was an impulse that needed to be suppressed in order for the good life, whether personal or collective, ethical or political, to flourish.  Though we now take it for granted, desire as a constitutive dimension of human nature and a positive force required a radical transformation, which coincided with the emergence of liberalism.   By critically exploring Foucault's claim that Western civilization is a civilization of desire, de Beistegui crafts a provocative and original genealogy of this shift in thinking. He shows how the relationship between identity, desire, and government has been harnessed and transformed in the modern world, shaping our relations with others and ourselves, and establishing desire as an essential driving force for the constitution of a new and better social order. But is it? The Government of Desire argues that this is precisely what a contemporary politics of resistance must seek to overcome. By questioning the supposed universality of a politics based on recognition and the economic satisfaction of desire, de Beistegui raises the crucial question of how we can manage to be less governed today, and explores contemporary forms of counter-conduct. ​Drawing on a host of thinkers from philosophy, political theory, and psychoanalysis, and concluding with a call for a sovereign and anarchic form of desire, The Government of Desire is a groundbreaking account of our freedom and unfreedom, of what makes us both governed and ungovernable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aRecognition (Philosophy) 0aSexxPolitical aspects. 4a(neo)liberalism. 4aFoucault. 4adesire. 4agenealogy. 4agovernmentality. 4apower. 4arecognition. 4aresistance. 4asexuality. 4asubjectivity. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226547404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226547404.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles